<dl id="n53097b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53097b">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53097b"> 97(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> platoon, <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53097b"><li>FW 348.18 </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/lexmd.htm#n53097b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/l39md.htm#n53097b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53097b">MS BL 47480-89v</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:170 <a name="mdd5" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mdd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/md/mdd5.htm#n53097b">Draft: II.3&sect;4.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Should you ever wander round the ranks of the North Sussex and inspect the faces of the men in that celebrated battalion, you will find that the majority are of the type bovine. They are a magnificent, if a stolid crowd, and their fighting record is second to none; but as might be expected in a regiment recruited largely from those who have been born and bred on the land, the prevalent expression of countenance is wooden. And in the rear rank of Number Three <mark>Platoon</mark>&mdash;at least that is where he used to exist beautifully&mdash;you will find the winner of the competition. <small> H.C. McNeile (&ldquo;Sapper&rdquo;) <a name="SJW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SJW"><cite title="source">John Walters</cite></a> (1927) The Awakening of John Walters, 7</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: [Army slang] Platoon: a quarter of a Company, about 50 men. [In text with Platonic.] </mm> </dd></dl>
